# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: face-recognition-cv
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:face-recognition-cv/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] During SSL, the model learns in two steps.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] First, the task is solved based on an auxiliary or pretext classification task using pseudo-labels, which help to initialize the model parameters.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Next, the actual task is performed with supervised or unsupervised learning.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Self-supervised learning has produced promising results in recent years, and has found practical application in fields such as audio processing, and is being used by Facebook and others for speech recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Pseudo-labels are automatically generated labels that a model assigns to unlabeled data based on its own predictions.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] They are widely used in self-supervised and semi-supervised learning, where ground-truth annotations are limited or unavailable.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] By treating predicted labels as surrogate ground truth, learning algorithms can make use of large quantities of unlabeled data in the training process.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Pseudo-labeling also plays an important role in systems that must adapt to concept drift, where the statistical properties of the data change over time.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] In these scenarios, the model may detect that an incoming instance deviates from previously learned behavior.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] The system then generates a classification result for that instance, and this predicted class is used as a pseudo-label for updating or retraining model components that are becoming outdated.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] This approach enables continuous adaptation in dynamic environments without requiring manual annotation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] In many adaptive learning pipelines, pseudo-labels are chosen when the classifier produces sufficiently confident predictions, reducing the risk of propagating errors.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] These pseudo-labeled instances are then incorporated into training to refresh or evolve the model's understanding of emerging data patterns, particularly when existing components show signs of “aging” due to drift or distributional shifts.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] This strategy reduces reliance on manual labeling while helping maintain long-term model performance.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Autoassociative self-supervised learning is a specific category of self-supervised learning where a neural network is trained to reproduce or reconstruct its own input data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] In other words, the model is tasked with learning a representation of the data that captures its essential features or structure, allowing it to regenerate the original input.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] The term "autoassociative" comes from the fact that the model is essentially associating the input data with itself.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] This is often achieved using autoencoders, which are a type of neural network architecture used for representation learning.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Autoencoders consist of an *encoder* network that maps the input data to a lower-dimensional representation (latent space), and a *decoder* network that reconstructs the input from this representation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] The training process involves presenting the model with input data and requiring it to reconstruct the same data as closely as possible.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] The loss function used during training typically penalizes the difference between the original input and the reconstructed output (e.g. mean squared error).
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] By minimizing this reconstruction error, the autoencoder learns a meaningful representation of the data in its latent space.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] For a binary classification task, training data can be divided into positive examples and negative examples.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Positive examples are those that match the target.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] For example, if training a classifier to identify birds, the positive training data would include images that contain birds.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Negative examples would be images that do not.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Contrastive self-supervised learning uses both positive and negative examples.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] The loss function in contrastive learning is used to minimize the distance between positive sample pairs, while maximizing the distance between negative sample pairs.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] An early example uses a pair of 1-dimensional convolutional neural networks to process a pair of images and maximize their agreement.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Contrastive Language-Image Pre-training (CLIP) allows joint pretraining of a text encoder and an image encoder, such that a matching image-text pair have image encoding vector and text encoding vector that span a small angle (having a large cosine similarity).
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] InfoNCE (Noise-Contrastive Estimation) is a method to optimize two models jointly, based on Noise Contrastive Estimation (NCE).
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Non-contrastive self-supervised learning (NCSSL) uses only positive examples.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Counterintuitively, NCSSL converges on a useful local minimum rather than reaching a trivial solution, with zero loss.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] For the example of binary classification, it would trivially learn to classify each example as positive.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Effective NCSSL requires an extra predictor on the online side that does not back-propagate on the target side.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] A major class of self-supervised learning moves beyond contrastive pairs, instead maximizing the agreement between views while preventing collapse through statistical constraints.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Rooted in Deep Canonical Correlation Analysis (Deep CCA), this approach includes Joint-Embedding Architectures (JEA) like Barlow Twins and VICReg, which enforce covariance constraints to learn invariant representations without negative sampling.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Deep Latent Variable Path Modelling (DLVPM) generalizes this to multimodal systems, using path models to enforce correlation and orthogonality across diverse data types.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] In 2022 Yann LeCun introduced Joint-Embedding Predictive Architectures (JEPA) as a step towards decision making, reasoning, and autonomous human intelligence in machines, including self-improvement through autonomous learning.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Founded in representation learning, LeCun included the concept of a “world model” in JEPA which aims to enable machines to replicate human intellect by providing machines with a concept for the world in which they exist.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Unlike autoencoders, JEPAs operate entirely in latent space, avoiding pixel-level noise to focus on semantic structure.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Rather than just learning invariance, JEPAs learn by predicting masked latent representations from visible context.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] JEPA has been applied to domains such as image analysis, audio processing, and motion in images and video.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] SSL belongs to supervised learning methods insofar as the goal is to generate a classified output from the input.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] At the same time, however, it does not require the explicit use of labeled input-output pairs.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Instead, correlations, metadata embedded in the data, or domain knowledge present in the input are implicitly and autonomously extracted from the data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] These supervisory signals, extracted from the data, can then be used for training.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] SSL is similar to unsupervised learning in that it does not require labels in the sample data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Unlike unsupervised learning, however, learning is not done using inherent data structures.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Semi-supervised learning combines supervised and unsupervised learning, requiring only a small portion of the learning data be labeled.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] In transfer learning, a model designed for one task is reused on a different task.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Training an autoencoder intrinsically constitutes a self-supervised process, because the output pattern needs to become an optimal reconstruction of the input pattern itself.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] However, in current jargon, the term 'self-supervised' often refers to tasks based on a pretext-task training setup.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] This involves the (human) design of such pretext task(s), unlike the case of fully self-contained autoencoder training.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] In reinforcement learning, self-supervising learning from a combination of losses can create abstract representations where only the most important information about the state are kept in a compressed way.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Self-supervised learning is particularly suitable for speech recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] For example, Facebook developed *wav2vec*, a self-supervised algorithm, to perform speech recognition using two deep convolutional neural networks that build on each other.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Google's Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers (BERT) model is used to better understand the context of search queries.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] OpenAI's GPT-3 is an autoregressive language model that can be used in language processing.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] It can be used to translate texts or answer questions, among other things.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] The Yarowsky algorithm is an example of self-supervised learning in natural language processing.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] From a small number of labeled examples, it learns to predict which word sense of a polysemous word is being used at a given point in text.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] DirectPred is a NCSSL that directly sets the predictor weights instead of learning it via typical gradient descent.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Self-GenomeNet is an example of self-supervised learning in genomics.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] SelfAPR is an example of self-supervised learning applied to automated program repair, where a neural model is trained on perturbations of a previous version of the program under repair and uses test execution diagnostics to synthesize patches.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Self-supervised learning continues to gain prominence as a new approach across diverse fields.
[src:face-recognition-cv/contrastive-learning] Its ability to leverage unlabeled data effectively opens new possibilities for advancement in machine learning, especially in data-driven application domains.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A **convolutional neural network** (**CNN**) is a type of feedforward neural network that learns features via filter (or kernel) optimization.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This type of deep learning network has been applied to process and make predictions from many different types of data including text, images and audio.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are the de-facto standard in deep learning-based approaches to computer vision and image processing, and have only recently been replaced—in some cases—by newer architectures such as the transformer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Vanishing gradients and exploding gradients, seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks, are prevented by the regularization that comes from using shared weights over fewer connections.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, for *each* neuron in the fully-connected layer, 10,000 weights would be required for processing an image sized 100 × 100 pixels.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, applying cascaded *convolution* (or cross-correlation) kernels, only 25 weights for each convolutional layer are required to process 5x5-sized tiles.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Higher-layer features are extracted from wider context windows, compared to lower-layer features.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs are also known as **shift invariant** or **space invariant artificial neural networks**, based on the shared-weight architecture of the convolution kernels or filters that slide along input features and provide translation-equivariant responses known as feature maps.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Counter-intuitively, most convolutional neural networks are not invariant to translation, due to the downsampling operation they apply to the input.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Feedforward neural networks are usually fully connected networks, that is, each neuron in one layer is connected to all neurons in the next layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "full connectivity" of these networks makes them prone to overfitting data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks were inspired by biological processes in that the connectivity pattern between neurons resembles the organization of the animal visual cortex.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Individual cortical neurons respond to stimuli only in a restricted region of the visual field known as the receptive field.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The receptive fields of different neurons partially overlap such that they cover the entire visual field.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use relatively little pre-processing compared to other image classification algorithms.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This means that the network learns to optimize the filters (or kernels) through automated learning, whereas in traditional algorithms these filters are hand-engineered.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This simplifies and automates the process, enhancing efficiency and scalability overcoming human-intervention bottlenecks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A convolutional neural network consists of an input layer, hidden layers and an output layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional neural network, the hidden layers include one or more layers that perform convolutions.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typically this includes a layer that performs a dot product of the convolution kernel with the layer's input matrix.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This product is usually the Frobenius inner product, and its activation function is commonly ReLU.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As the convolution kernel slides along the input matrix for the layer, the convolution operation generates a feature map, which in turn contributes to the input of the next layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is followed by other layers such as pooling layers, fully connected layers, and normalization layers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Here it should be noted how close a convolutional neural network is to a matched filter.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (number of inputs) × (feature map height) × (feature map width) × (feature map channels).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional layers convolve the input and pass its result to the next layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to the response of a neuron in the visual cortex to a specific stimulus.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each convolutional neuron processes data only for its receptive field.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although fully connected feedforward neural networks can be used to learn features and classify data, this architecture is generally impractical for larger inputs (e.g., high-resolution images), which would require massive numbers of neurons because each pixel is a relevant input feature.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A fully connected layer for an image of size 100 × 100 has 10,000 weights for *each* neuron in the second layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution reduces the number of free parameters, allowing the network to be deeper.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, using a 5 × 5 tiling region, each with the same shared weights, requires only 25 neurons.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using shared weights means there are many fewer parameters, which helps avoid the vanishing gradients and exploding gradients problems seen during backpropagation in earlier neural networks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To speed processing, standard convolutional layers can be replaced by depthwise separable convolutional layers, which are based on a depthwise convolution followed by a pointwise convolution.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The *depthwise convolution* is a spatial convolution applied independently over each channel of the input tensor, while the *pointwise convolution* is a standard convolution restricted to the use of $1\times 1$ kernels.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks may include local and/or global pooling layers along with traditional convolutional layers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling layers reduce the dimensions of data by combining the outputs of neuron clusters at one layer into a single neuron in the next layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Local pooling combines small clusters, tiling sizes such as 2 × 2 are commonly used.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Global pooling acts on all the neurons of the feature map.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are two common types of pooling in popular use: max and average.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] *Max pooling* uses the maximum value of each local cluster of neurons in the feature map, while *average pooling* takes the average value.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fully connected layers connect every neuron in one layer to every neuron in another layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the same as a traditional multilayer perceptron neural network (MLP).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in the fully connected layer receives input from all the neurons in the previous layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These inputs are weighted and summed with the corresponding biases, and then passed through an activation function to perform a nonlinear transformation, generating the output.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The flattened matrix goes through a fully connected layer to classify the images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In neural networks, each neuron receives input from some number of locations in the previous layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a convolutional layer, each neuron receives input from only a restricted area of the previous layer called the neuron's *receptive field*.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Whereas, in a fully connected layer, the receptive field is the *entire previous layer*.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, in each convolutional layer, each neuron takes input from a larger area in the input than previous layers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is due to applying the convolution over and over, which takes the value of a pixel into account, as well as its surrounding pixels.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When using dilated layers, the number of pixels in the receptive field remains constant, but the field is more sparsely populated as its dimensions grow when combining the effect of several layers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To manipulate the receptive field size as desired, there are some alternatives to the standard convolutional layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, atrous or dilated convolution expands the receptive field size without increasing the number of parameters by interleaving visible and blind regions.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Moreover, a single dilated convolutional layer can comprise filters with multiple dilation ratios, thus having a variable receptive field size.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each neuron in a neural network computes an output value by applying a specific function to the input values received from the receptive field in the previous layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The function that is applied to the input values is determined by a vector of weights and a bias (typically real numbers).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning consists of iteratively adjusting these biases and weights.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The vectors of weights and biases are called *filters* and represent particular features of the input (e.g., a particular shape).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A distinguishing feature of CNNs is that many neurons can share the same filter.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces the memory footprint because a single bias and a single vector of weights are used across all receptive fields that share that filter, as opposed to each receptive field having its own bias and vector weighting.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional neural network is essentially the reverse of a CNN.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It consists of deconvolutional layers and unpooling layers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A deconvolutional layer is the transpose of a convolutional layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Specifically, a convolutional layer can be written as a multiplication with a matrix, and a deconvolutional layer is multiplication with the transpose of that matrix.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The max-unpooling layer is the simplest, as it simply copies each entry multiple times.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a 2-by-2 max-unpooling layer is $[x]\mapsto {\begin{bmatrix}x&x\\x&x\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Deconvolution layers are used in image generators.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By default, it creates periodic checkerboard artifact, which can be fixed by upscale-then-convolve.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNN are often compared to the way the brain achieves vision processing in living organisms.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Work by Hubel and Wiesel in the 1950s and 1960s showed that cat visual cortices contain neurons that individually respond to small regions of the visual field.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Provided the eyes are not moving, the region of visual space within which visual stimuli affect the firing of a single neuron is known as its receptive field.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neighboring cells have similar and overlapping receptive fields.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Receptive field size and location varies systematically across the cortex to form a complete map of visual space.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The cortex in each hemisphere represents the contralateral visual field.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hubel and Wiesel also proposed a cascading model of these two types of cells for use in pattern recognition tasks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same paper, Fukushima also introduced the ReLU (rectified linear unit) activation function.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "neocognitron" was introduced by Fukushima in 1980.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Several supervised and unsupervised learning algorithms have been proposed over the decades to train the weights of a neocognitron.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Today, however, the CNN architecture is usually trained through backpropagation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Fukushima's ReLU activation function was not used in his neocognitron since all the weights were nonnegative; lateral inhibition was used instead.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The rectifier has become a very popular activation function for CNNs and deep neural networks in general.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The term "convolution" first appears in neural networks in a paper by Toshiteru Homma, Les Atlas, and Robert Marks II at the first Conference on Neural Information Processing Systems in 1987.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their paper replaced multiplication with convolution in time, inherently providing shift invariance, motivated by and connecting more directly to the signal-processing concept of a filter, and demonstrated it on a speech recognition task.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They also pointed out that as a data-trainable system, convolution is essentially equivalent to correlation since reversal of the weights does not affect the final learned function ("For convenience, we denote * as correlation instead of convolution.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that convolving a(t) with b(t) is equivalent to correlating a(-t) with b(t).").
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Modern CNN implementations typically do correlation and call it convolution, for convenience, as they did here.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The time delay neural network (TDNN) was introduced in 1987 by Alex Waibel et al. for phoneme recognition and was an early convolutional network exhibiting shift-invariance.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A TDNN is a 1-D convolutional neural net where the convolution is performed along the time axis of the data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is the first CNN utilizing weight sharing in combination with a training by gradient descent, using backpropagation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, while also using a pyramidal structure as in the neocognitron, it performed a global optimization of the weights instead of a local one.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs are convolutional networks that share weights along the temporal dimension.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They allow speech signals to be processed time-invariantly.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Hampshire and Waibel introduced a variant that performs a two-dimensional convolution.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since these TDNNs operated on spectrograms, the resulting phoneme recognition system was invariant to both time and frequency shifts, as with images processed by a neocognitron.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] TDNNs improved the performance of far-distance speech recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) designed a 2-D CNN system to recognize hand-written ZIP Code numbers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the lack of an efficient training method to determine the kernel coefficients of the involved convolutions meant that all the coefficients had to be laboriously hand-designed.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Following the advances in the training of 1-D CNNs by Waibel et al.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1989) used back-propagation to learn the convolution kernel coefficients directly from images of hand-written numbers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Learning was thus fully automatic, performed better than manual coefficient design, and was suited to a broader range of image recognition problems and image types.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (1988) used back-propagation to train the convolution kernels of a CNN for alphabets recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was called shift-invariant pattern recognition neural network before the name CNN was coined later in the early 1990s.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Wei Zhang et al. also applied the same CNN without the last fully connected layer for medical image object segmentation (1991) and breast cancer detection in mammograms (1994).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach became a foundation of modern computer vision.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 1990 Yamaguchi et al. introduced the concept of max pooling, a fixed filtering operation that calculates and propagates the maximum value of a given region.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] They did so by combining TDNNs with max pooling to realize a speaker-independent isolated word recognition system.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In their system they used several TDNNs per word, one for each syllable.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The results of each TDNN over the input signal were combined using max pooling and the outputs of the pooling layers were then passed on to networks performing the actual word classification.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In a variant of the neocognitron called the *cresceptron*, instead of using Fukushima's spatial averaging with inhibition and saturation, J.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weng et al. in 1993 used max pooling, where a downsampling unit computes the maximum of the activations of the units in its patch, introducing this method into the vision field.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is often used in modern CNNs.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] LeNet-5, a pioneering 7-level convolutional network by LeCun et al. in 1995, classifies hand-written numbers on checks digitized in 32×32 pixel images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The ability to process higher-resolution images requires larger and more layers of convolutional neural networks, so this technique is constrained by the availability of computing resources.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was superior than other commercial courtesy amount reading systems (as of 1995).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The system was integrated in NCR's check reading systems, and fielded in several American banks since June 1996, reading millions of checks per day.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A shift-invariant neural network was proposed by Wei Zhang et al. for image character recognition in 1988.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is a modified Neocognitron by keeping only the convolutional interconnections between the image feature layers and the last fully connected layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model was trained with back-propagation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The training algorithm was further improved in 1991 to improve its generalization ability.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The model architecture was modified by removing the last fully connected layer and applied for medical image segmentation (1991) and automatic detection of breast cancer in mammograms (1994).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A different convolution-based design was proposed in 1988 for application to decomposition of one-dimensional electromyography convolved signals via de-convolution.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This design was modified in 1989 to other de-convolution-based designs.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Although CNNs were invented in the 1980s, their breakthrough in the 2000s required fast implementations on graphics processing units (GPUs).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Jung that standard neural networks can be greatly accelerated on GPUs.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 20 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2005, another paper also emphasised the value of GPGPU for machine learning.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The first GPU-implementation of a CNN was described in 2006 by K.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their implementation was 4 times faster than an equivalent implementation on CPU.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the same period, GPUs were also used for unsupervised training of deep belief networks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2010, Dan Ciresan et al. at IDSIA trained deep feedforward networks on GPUs.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, they extended this to CNNs, accelerating by 60 compared to training CPU.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, the network won an image recognition contest where they achieved superhuman performance for the first time.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Then they won more competitions and achieved state of the art on several benchmarks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Subsequently, AlexNet, a similar GPU-based CNN by Alex Krizhevsky et al. won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was an early catalytic event for the AI boom.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Compared to the training of CNNs using GPUs, not much attention was given to CPU.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] (Viebke et al 2019) parallelizes CNN by thread- and SIMD-level parallelism that is available on the Intel Xeon Phi.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the past, traditional multilayer perceptron (MLP) models were used for image recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, the full connectivity between nodes caused the curse of dimensionality, and was computationally intractable with higher-resolution images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A 1000×1000-pixel image with RGB color channels has 3 million weights per fully-connected neuron, which is too high to feasibly process efficiently at scale.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, in CIFAR-10, images are only of size 32×32×3 (32 wide, 32 high, 3 color channels), so a single fully connected neuron in the first hidden layer of a regular neural network would have 32*32*3 = 3,072 weights.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Also, such network architecture does not take into account the spatial structure of data, treating input pixels which are far apart in the same way as pixels that are close together.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This ignores locality of reference in data with a grid-topology (such as images), both computationally and semantically.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Thus, full connectivity of neurons is wasteful for purposes such as image recognition that are dominated by spatially local input patterns.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional neural networks are variants of multilayer perceptrons, designed to emulate the behavior of a visual cortex.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] These models mitigate the challenges posed by the MLP architecture by exploiting the strong spatially local correlation present in natural images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Together, these properties allow CNNs to achieve better generalization on vision problems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Weight sharing dramatically reduces the number of free parameters learned, thus lowering the memory requirements for running the network and allowing the training of larger, more powerful networks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A CNN architecture is formed by a stack of distinct layers that transform the input volume into an output volume (e.g. holding the class scores) through a differentiable function.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A few distinct types of layers are commonly used.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The convolutional layer is the core building block of a CNN.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The layer's parameters consist of a set of learnable filters (or kernels), which have a small receptive field, but extend through the full depth of the input volume.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] During the forward pass, each filter is convolved across the width and height of the input volume, computing the dot product between the filter entries and the input, producing a 2-dimensional activation map of that filter.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As a result, the network learns filters that activate when it detects some specific type of feature at some spatial position in the input.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Stacking the activation maps for all filters along the depth dimension forms the full output volume of the convolution layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Every entry in the output volume can thus also be interpreted as an output of a neuron that looks at a small region in the input.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each entry in an activation map use the same set of parameters that define the filter.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Self-supervised learning has been adapted for use in convolutional layers by using sparse patches with a high-mask ratio and a global response normalization layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] When dealing with high-dimensional inputs such as images, it is impractical to connect neurons to all neurons in the previous volume because such a network architecture does not take the spatial structure of the data into account.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolutional networks exploit spatially local correlation by enforcing a sparse local connectivity pattern between neurons of adjacent layers: each neuron is connected to only a small region of the input volume.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The extent of this connectivity is a hyperparameter called the receptive field of the neuron.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The connections are local in space (along width and height), but always extend along the entire depth of the input volume.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Such an architecture ensures that the learned filters produce the strongest response to a spatially local input pattern.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The spatial size of the output volume is a function of the input volume size W , the kernel field size K of the convolutional layer neurons, the stride S , and the amount of zero padding P on the border.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] If this number is not an integer, then the strides are incorrect and the neurons cannot be tiled to fit across the input volume in a symmetric way.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In general, setting zero padding to be ${\textstyle P=(K-1)/2}$ when the stride is $S=1$ ensures that the input volume and output volume will have the same size spatially.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, it is not always completely necessary to use all of the neurons of the previous layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a neural network designer may decide to use just a portion of padding.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A parameter sharing scheme is used in convolutional layers to control the number of free parameters.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It relies on the assumption that if a patch feature is useful to compute at some spatial position, then it should also be useful to compute at other positions.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Denoting a single 2-dimensional slice of depth as a *depth slice*, the neurons in each depth slice are constrained to use the same weights and bias.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since all neurons in a single depth slice share the same parameters, the forward pass in each depth slice of the convolutional layer can be computed as a convolution of the neuron's weights with the input volume.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Therefore, it is common to refer to the sets of weights as a filter (or a kernel), which is convolved with the input.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The result of this convolution is an activation map, and the set of activation maps for each different filter are stacked together along the depth dimension to produce the output volume.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Parameter sharing contributes to the translation invariance of the CNN architecture.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sometimes, the parameter sharing assumption may not make sense.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is especially the case when the input images to a CNN have some specific centered structure; for which we expect completely different features to be learned on different spatial locations.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One practical example is when the inputs are faces that have been centered in the image: we might expect different eye-specific or hair-specific features to be learned in different parts of the image.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In that case it is common to relax the parameter sharing scheme, and instead simply call the layer a "locally connected layer".
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In this layer, the convolutional kernels' parameters are not shared.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Instead, the network learns independent weights and biases for each spatial location.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This allows each location to have its own feature-learning ability, making it better suited to handle images with distinct central structures or irregular features.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another important concept of CNNs is pooling, which is used as a form of non-linear down-sampling.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling provides downsampling because it reduces the spatial dimensions (height and width) of the input feature maps while retaining the most important information.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] There are several non-linear functions to implement pooling, where *max pooling* and *average pooling* are the most common.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Pooling aggregates information from small regions of the input creating partitions of the input feature map, typically using a fixed-size window (like 2x2) and applying a stride (often 2) to move the window across the input.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that without using a stride greater than 1, pooling would not perform downsampling, as it would simply move the pooling window across the input one step at a time, without reducing the size of the feature map.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the stride is what actually causes the downsampling by determining how much the pooling window moves over the input.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Intuitively, the exact location of a feature is less important than its rough location relative to other features.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the idea behind the use of pooling in convolutional neural networks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer serves to progressively reduce the spatial size of the representation, to reduce the number of parameters, memory footprint and amount of computation in the network, and hence to also control overfitting.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is common to periodically insert a pooling layer between successive convolutional layers (each one typically followed by an activation function, such as a ReLU layer) in a CNN architecture.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] While pooling layers contribute to local translation invariance, they do not provide global translation invariance in a CNN, unless a form of global pooling is used.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The pooling layer commonly operates independently on every depth, or slice, of the input and resizes it spatially.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The depth dimension remains unchanged (this is true for other forms of pooling as well).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In addition to max pooling, pooling units can use other functions, such as average pooling or ℓ2-norm pooling.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Average pooling was often used historically but has recently fallen out of favor compared to max pooling, which generally performs better in practice.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to the effects of fast spatial reduction of the size of the representation, there is a recent trend towards using smaller filters or discarding pooling layers altogether.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A channel max pooling (CMP) operation layer conducts the MP operation along the channel side among the corresponding positions of the consecutive feature maps for the purpose of redundant information elimination.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The CMP makes the significant features gather together within fewer channels, which is important for fine-grained image classification that needs more discriminating features.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Meanwhile, another advantage of the CMP operation is to make the channel number of feature maps smaller before it connects to the first fully connected (FC) layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Similar to the MP operation, we denote the input feature maps and output feature maps of a CMP layer as F ∈ R(C×M×N) and C ∈ R(c×M×N), respectively, where C and c are the channel numbers of the input and output feature maps, M and N are the widths and the height of the feature maps, respectively.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Note that the CMP operation only changes the channel number of the feature maps.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The width and the height of the feature maps are not changed, which is different from the MP operation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is the abbreviation of rectified linear unit.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It was proposed by Alston Householder in 1941, and used in CNN by Kunihiko Fukushima in 1969.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU applies the non-saturating activation function ${\textstyle f(x)=\max(0,x)}$ .
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It effectively removes negative values from an activation map by setting them to zero.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It introduces nonlinearity to the decision function and in the overall network without affecting the receptive fields of the convolution layers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In 2011, Xavier Glorot, Antoine Bordes and Yoshua Bengio found that ReLU enables better training of deeper networks, compared to widely used activation functions prior to 2011.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other functions can also be used to increase nonlinearity, for example the saturating hyperbolic tangent $f(x)=\tanh(x)$ , $f(x)=|\tanh(x)|$ , and the sigmoid function ${\textstyle \sigma (x)=(1+e^{-x})^{-1}}$ .
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] ReLU is often preferred to other functions because it trains the neural network several times faster without a significant penalty to generalization accuracy.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] After several convolutional and max pooling layers, the final classification is done via fully connected layers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Neurons in a fully connected layer have connections to all activations in the previous layer, as seen in regular (non-convolutional) artificial neural networks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Their activations can thus be computed as an affine transformation, with matrix multiplication followed by a bias offset (vector addition of a learned or fixed bias term).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The "loss layer", or "loss function", exemplifies how training penalizes the deviation between the predicted output of the network, and the true data labels (during supervised learning).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Various loss functions can be used, depending on the specific task.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The Softmax loss function is used for predicting a single class of *K* mutually exclusive classes.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Sigmoid cross-entropy loss is used for predicting *K* independent probability values in $[0,1]$ .
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Euclidean loss is used for regressing to real-valued labels $(-\infty ,\infty )$ .
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Hyperparameters are various settings that are used to control the learning process.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use more hyperparameters than a standard multilayer perceptron (MLP).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Padding is the addition of (typically) 0-valued pixels on the borders of an image.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is done so that the border pixels are not undervalued (lost) from the output because they would ordinarily participate in only a single receptive field instance.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The padding applied is typically one less than the corresponding kernel dimension.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, a convolutional layer using 3x3 kernels would receive a 2-pixel pad, that is 1 pixel on each side of the image.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The stride is the number of pixels that the analysis window moves on each iteration.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A stride of 2 means that each kernel is offset by 2 pixels from its predecessor.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Since feature map size decreases with depth, layers near the input layer tend to have fewer filters while higher layers can have more.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] To equalize computation at each layer, the product of feature values *va* with pixel position is kept roughly constant across layers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Preserving more information about the input would require keeping the total number of activations (number of feature maps times number of pixel positions) non-decreasing from one layer to the next.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The number of feature maps directly controls the capacity and depends on the number of available examples and task complexity.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Common filter sizes found in the literature vary greatly, and are usually chosen based on the data set.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Typical filter sizes range from 1x1 to 7x7.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] As two famous examples, AlexNet used 3x3, 5x5, and 11x11.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The challenge is to find the right level of granularity so as to create abstractions at the proper scale, given a particular data set, and without overfitting.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Max pooling is typically used, often with a 2x2 dimension.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This implies that the input is drastically downsampled, reducing processing cost.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Greater pooling reduces the dimension of the signal, and may result in unacceptable information loss.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Often, non-overlapping pooling windows perform best.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Dilation involves ignoring pixels within a kernel.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This reduces processing memory potentially without significant signal loss.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A dilation of 2 on a 3x3 kernel expands the kernel to 5x5, while still processing 9 (evenly spaced) pixels.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Accordingly, dilation of 4 expands the kernel to 7x7.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It is commonly assumed that CNNs are invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Convolution or pooling layers within a CNN that do not have a stride greater than one are indeed equivariant to translations of the input.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Furthermore, if a CNN makes use of fully connected layers, translation equivariance does not imply translation invariance, as the fully connected layers are not invariant to shifts of the input.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One solution for complete translation invariance is avoiding any down-sampling throughout the network and applying global average pooling at the last layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Additionally, several other partial solutions have been proposed, such as anti-aliasing before downsampling operations, spatial transformer networks, data augmentation, subsampling combined with pooling, and capsule neural networks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The accuracy of the final model is typically estimated on a sub-part of the dataset set apart at the start, often called a test set.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Alternatively, methods such as *k*-fold cross-validation are applied.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Other strategies include using conformal prediction.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Regularization is a process of introducing additional information to solve an ill-posed problem or to prevent overfitting.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] CNNs use various types of regularization.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because networks have so many parameters, they are prone to overfitting.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One method to reduce overfitting is dropout, introduced in 2014.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At each training stage, individual nodes are either "dropped out" of the net (ignored) with probability $1-p$ or kept with probability p , so that a reduced network is left; incoming and outgoing edges to a dropped-out node are also removed.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Only the reduced network is trained on the data in that stage.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The removed nodes are then reinserted into the network with their original weights.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In the training stages, p is usually 0.5; for input nodes, it is typically much higher because information is directly lost when input nodes are ignored.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] At testing time after training has finished, we would ideally like to find a sample average of all possible $2^{n}$ dropped-out networks; unfortunately this is unfeasible for large values of n .
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] However, we can find an approximation by using the full network with each node's output weighted by a factor of p , so the expected value of the output of any node is the same as in the training stages.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is the biggest contribution of the dropout method: although it effectively generates $2^{n}$ neural nets, and as such allows for model combination, at test time only a single network needs to be tested.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] By avoiding training all nodes on all training data, dropout decreases overfitting.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The method also significantly improves training speed.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This makes the model combination practical, even for deep neural networks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The technique seems to reduce node interactions, leading them to learn more robust features that better generalize to new data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is the generalization of dropout in which each connection, rather than each output unit, can be dropped with probability $1-p$ .
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Each unit thus receives input from a random subset of units in the previous layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] DropConnect is similar to dropout as it introduces dynamic sparsity within the model, but differs in that the sparsity is on the weights, rather than the output vectors of a layer.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, the fully connected layer with DropConnect becomes a sparsely connected layer in which the connections are chosen at random during the training stage.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A major drawback to dropout is that it does not have the same benefits for convolutional layers, where the neurons are not fully connected.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This approach is free of hyperparameters and can be combined with other regularization approaches, such as dropout and data augmentation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] An alternate view of stochastic pooling is that it is equivalent to standard max pooling but with many copies of an input image, each having small local deformations.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] This is similar to explicit elastic deformations of the input images, which delivers excellent performance on the MNIST data set.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Using stochastic pooling in a multilayer model gives an exponential number of deformations since the selections in higher layers are independent of those below.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because the degree of model overfitting is determined by both its power and the amount of training it receives, providing a convolutional network with more training examples can reduce overfitting.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Because there is often not enough available data to train, especially considering that some part should be spared for later testing, two approaches are to either generate new data from scratch (if possible) or perturb existing data to create new ones.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For example, input images can be cropped, rotated, or rescaled to create new examples with the same labels as the original training set.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] One of the simplest methods to prevent overfitting of a network is to simply stop the training before overfitting has had a chance to occur.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It comes with the disadvantage that the learning process is halted.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another simple way to prevent overfitting is to limit the number of parameters, typically by limiting the number of hidden units in each layer or limiting network depth.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] For convolutional networks, the filter size also affects the number of parameters.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Limiting the number of parameters restricts the predictive power of the network directly, reducing the complexity of the function that it can perform on the data, and thus limits the amount of overfitting.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] A simple form of added regularizer is weight decay, which simply adds an additional error, proportional to the sum of weights (L1 norm) or squared magnitude (L2 norm) of the weight vector, to the error at each node.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The level of acceptable model complexity can be reduced by increasing the proportionality constant('alpha' hyperparameter), thus increasing the penalty for large weight vectors.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L2 regularization is the most common form of regularization.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It can be implemented by penalizing the squared magnitude of all parameters directly in the objective.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] The L2 regularization has the intuitive interpretation of heavily penalizing peaky weight vectors and preferring diffuse weight vectors.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Due to multiplicative interactions between weights and inputs this has the useful property of encouraging the network to use all of its inputs a little rather than some of its inputs a lot.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] It makes the weight vectors sparse during optimization.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In other words, neurons with L1 regularization end up using only a sparse subset of their most important inputs and become nearly invariant to the noisy inputs.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] L1 with L2 regularization can be combined; this is called elastic net regularization.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Another form of regularization is to enforce an absolute upper bound on the magnitude of the weight vector for every neuron and use projected gradient descent to enforce the constraint.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] In practice, this corresponds to performing the parameter update as normal, and then enforcing the constraint by clamping the weight vector ${\vec {w}}$ of every neuron to satisfy $\|{\vec {w}}\|_{2}<c$ .
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p01] Some papers report improvements when using this form of regularization.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Pooling loses the precise spatial relationships between high-level parts (such as nose and mouth in a face image).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] These relationships are needed for identity recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Overlapping the pools so that each feature occurs in multiple pools, helps retain the information.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Translation alone cannot extrapolate the understanding of geometric relationships to a radically new viewpoint, such as a different orientation or scale.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] On the other hand, people are very good at extrapolating; after seeing a new shape once they can recognize it from a different viewpoint.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] An earlier common way to deal with this problem is to train the network on transformed data in different orientations, scales, lighting, etc. so that the network can cope with these variations.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is computationally intensive for large data-sets.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The alternative is to use a hierarchy of coordinate frames and use a group of neurons to represent a conjunction of the shape of the feature and its pose relative to the retina.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The pose relative to the retina is the relationship between the coordinate frame of the retina and the intrinsic features' coordinate frame.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Thus, one way to represent something is to embed the coordinate frame within it.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This allows large features to be recognized by using the consistency of the poses of their parts (e.g. nose and mouth poses make a consistent prediction of the pose of the whole face).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This approach ensures that the higher-level entity (e.g. face) is present when the lower-level (e.g. nose and mouth) agree on its prediction of the pose.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The vectors of neuronal activity that represent pose ("pose vectors") allow spatial transformations modeled as linear operations that make it easier for the network to learn the hierarchy of visual entities and generalize across viewpoints.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] This is similar to the way the human visual system imposes coordinate frames in order to represent shapes.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs are often used in image recognition systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2012, an error rate of 0.23% on the MNIST database was reported.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper on using CNN for image classification reported that the learning process was "surprisingly fast"; in the same paper, the best published results as of 2011 were achieved in the MNIST database and the NORB database.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, a similar CNN called AlexNet won the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge 2012.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] When applied to facial recognition, CNNs achieved a large decrease in error rate.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another paper reported a 97.6% recognition rate on "5,600 still images of more than 10 subjects".
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs were used to assess video quality in an objective way after manual training; the resulting system had a very low root mean square error.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and hundreds of object classes.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In the ILSVRC 2014, a large-scale visual recognition challenge, almost every highly ranked team used CNN as their basic framework.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The winner GoogLeNet (the foundation of DeepDream) increased the mean average precision of object detection to 0.439329, and reduced classification error to 0.06656, the best result to date.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its network applied more than 30 layers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] That performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests was close to that of humans.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on a stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters, an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained categories such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, a many-layered CNN demonstrated the ability to spot faces from a wide range of angles, including upside down, even when partially occluded, with competitive performance.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The network was trained on a database of 200,000 images that included faces at various angles and orientations and a further 20 million images without faces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They used batches of 128 images over 50,000 iterations.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to image data domains, there is relatively little work on applying CNNs to video classification.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Video is more complex than images since it has another (temporal) dimension.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, some extensions of CNNs into the video domain have been explored.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] One approach is to treat space and time as equivalent dimensions of the input and perform convolutions in both time and space.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Another way is to fuse the features of two convolutional neural networks, one for the spatial and one for the temporal stream.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Long short-term memory (LSTM) recurrent units are typically incorporated after the CNN to account for inter-frame or inter-clip dependencies.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unsupervised learning schemes for training spatio-temporal features have been introduced, based on convolutional gated restricted Boltzmann machines and independent subspace analysis.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Its application can be seen in text-to-video models.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have also been explored for natural language processing.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNN models are effective for various NLP problems and achieved excellent results in semantic parsing, search query retrieval, sentence modeling, classification, prediction and other traditional NLP tasks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Compared to traditional language processing methods such as recurrent neural networks, CNNs can represent different contextual realities of language that do not rely on a series-sequence assumption, while RNNs are better suitable when classical time series modeling is required.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been applied in ecological and behavioral research to automatically detect and quantify animal behavior from visual data, enabling identification of animals, tracking of individuals, estimation of pose, and classification of specific actions such as feeding, and social interactions.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Combined with multi-object tracking and temporal modeling, these systems can extract behavioral sequences over extended recordings, reducing reliance on manual annotation and increasing throughput for studies of individual variation, social networks, and collective dynamics.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A CNN with 1-D convolutions was used on time series in the frequency domain (spectral residual) by an unsupervised model to detect anomalies in the time domain.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Predicting the interaction between molecules and biological proteins can identify potential treatments.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In 2015, Atomwise introduced AtomNet, the first deep learning neural network for structure-based drug design.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The system trains directly on 3-dimensional representations of chemical interactions.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Similar to how image recognition networks learn to compose smaller, spatially proximate features into larger, complex structures, AtomNet discovers chemical features, such as aromaticity, sp3 carbons, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Subsequently, AtomNet was used to predict novel candidate biomolecules for multiple disease targets, most notably treatments for the Ebola virus and multiple sclerosis.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs have been used in the game of checkers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] From 1999 to 2001, Fogel and Chellapilla published papers showing how a convolutional neural network could learn to play checkers using co-evolution.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The learning process did not use prior human professional games, but rather focused on a minimal set of information contained in the checkerboard: the location and type of pieces, and the difference in number of pieces between the two sides.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Ultimately, the program (Blondie24) was tested on 165 games against players and ranked in the highest 0.4%.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] It also earned a win against the program Chinook at its "expert" level of play.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In December 2014, Clark and Storkey published a paper showing that a CNN trained by supervised learning from a database of human professional games could outperform GNU Go and win some games against Monte Carlo tree search Fuego 1.1 in a fraction of the time it took Fuego to play.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Later it was announced that a large 12-layer convolutional neural network had correctly predicted the professional move in 55% of positions, equalling the accuracy of a 6 dan human player.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A couple of CNNs for choosing moves to try ("policy network") and evaluating positions ("value network") driving MCTS were used by AlphaGo, the first to beat the best human player at the time.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Recurrent neural networks are generally considered the best neural network architectures for time series forecasting (and sequence modeling in general), but recent studies show that convolutional networks can perform comparably or even better.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Dilated convolutions might enable one-dimensional convolutional neural networks to effectively learn time series dependences.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutions can be implemented more efficiently than RNN-based solutions, and they do not suffer from vanishing (or exploding) gradients.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional networks can provide an improved forecasting performance when there are multiple similar time series to learn from.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] CNNs can also be applied to further tasks in time series analysis (e.g., time series classification or quantile forecasting).
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] As archaeological findings such as clay tablets with cuneiform writing are increasingly acquired using 3D scanners, benchmark datasets are becoming available, including *HeiCuBeDa* providing almost 2000 normalized 2-D and 3-D datasets prepared with the GigaMesh Software Framework.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] So curvature-based measures are used in conjunction with geometric neural networks (GNNs), e.g. for period classification of those clay tablets being among the oldest documents of human history.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] For many applications, training data is not very available.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional neural networks usually require a large amount of training data in order to avoid overfitting.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A common technique is to train the network on a larger data set from a related domain.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Once the network parameters have converged an additional training step is performed using the in-domain data to fine-tune the network weights, this is known as transfer learning.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Furthermore, this technique allows convolutional network architectures to successfully be applied to problems with tiny training sets.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] End-to-end training and prediction are common practice in computer vision.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] However, human interpretable explanations are required for critical systems such as self-driving cars.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] With recent advances in visual salience, spatial attention, and temporal attention, the most critical spatial regions/temporal instants could be visualized to justify the CNN predictions.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] A deep Q-network (DQN) is a type of deep learning model that combines a deep neural network with Q-learning, a form of reinforcement learning.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Unlike earlier reinforcement learning agents, DQNs that utilize CNNs can learn directly from high-dimensional sensory inputs via reinforcement learning.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Preliminary results were presented in 2014, with an accompanying paper in February 2015.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The research described an application to Atari 2600 gaming.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Other deep reinforcement learning models preceded it.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Convolutional deep belief networks (CDBN) have structure very similar to convolutional neural networks and are trained similarly to deep belief networks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Therefore, they exploit the 2D structure of images, like CNNs do, and make use of pre-training like deep belief networks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] They provide a generic structure that can be used in many image and signal processing tasks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] Benchmark results on standard image datasets like CIFAR have been obtained using CDBNs.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The feed-forward architecture of convolutional neural networks was extended in the neural abstraction pyramid by lateral and feedback connections.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] The resulting recurrent convolutional network allows for the flexible incorporation of contextual information to iteratively resolve local ambiguities.
[src:face-recognition-cv/convolutional-neural-network-p02] In contrast to previous models, image-like outputs at the highest resolution were generated, e.g., for semantic segmentation, image reconstruction, and object localization tasks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] In data analysis, **cosine similarity** is a measure of similarity between two non-zero vectors defined in an inner product space.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity is the cosine of the angle between the vectors; that is, it is the dot product of the vectors divided by the product of their lengths.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] It follows that the cosine similarity does not depend on the magnitudes of the vectors, but only on their angle.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] The cosine similarity always belongs to the interval $[-1,+1].$ For example, two proportional vectors have a cosine similarity of +1, two orthogonal vectors have a similarity of 0, and two opposite vectors have a similarity of −1.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] In some contexts, the component values of the vectors cannot be negative, in which case the cosine similarity is bounded in $[0,1]$ .
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] For example, in information retrieval and text mining, each word is assigned a different coordinate and a document is represented by the vector of the numbers of occurrences of each word in the document.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity then gives a useful measure of how similar two documents are likely to be, in terms of their subject matter, and independently of the length of the documents.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] The technique is also used to measure cohesion within clusters in the field of data mining.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] One advantage of cosine similarity is its low complexity, especially for sparse vectors: only the non-zero coordinates need to be considered.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] Other names for cosine similarity include **Orchini similarity** and **Tucker coefficient of congruence**; the **Otsuka–Ochiai similarity** (see below) is cosine similarity applied to binary data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] where $A_{i}$ and $B_{i}$ are the i th components of vectors $\mathbf {A}$ and $\mathbf {B}$ , respectively.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] The resulting similarity ranges from −1 meaning exactly opposite, to +1 meaning exactly the same, with 0 indicating orthogonality (no correlation), while in-between values indicate intermediate similarity or dissimilarity.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] For text matching, the attribute vectors *A* and *B* are usually the term frequency vectors of the documents.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity can be seen as a method of normalizing document length during comparison.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] In the case of information retrieval, the cosine similarity of two documents will range from $0\to 1$ , since the term frequencies cannot be negative.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] This remains true when using TF-IDF weights.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] The angle between two term frequency vectors cannot be greater than 90°.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] If the attribute vectors are normalized by subtracting the vector means (e.g., $A-{\bar {A}}$ ), the measure is called the centered cosine similarity and is equivalent to the Pearson correlation coefficient.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] By virtue of being proportional to squared Euclidean distance, the cosine distance is not a true distance metric; it does not exhibit the triangle inequality property — or, more formally, the Schwarz inequality — and it violates the coincidence axiom.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] To repair the triangle inequality property while maintaining the same ordering, one can convert to Euclidean distance ${\textstyle {\sqrt {2(1-S_{C}(A,B))}}}$ or angular distance *θ* = arccos(*S**C*(*A*, *B*)).
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] Alternatively, the triangular inequality that does work for angular distances can be expressed directly in terms of the cosines; see below.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] The normalized angle, referred to as **angular distance**, between any two vectors A and B is a formal distance metric and can be calculated from the cosine similarity.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] The complement of the angular distance metric can then be used to define **angular similarity** function bounded between 0 and 1, inclusive.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] Unfortunately, computing the inverse cosine (arccos) function is slow, making the use of the angular distance more computationally expensive than using the more common (but not metric) cosine distance above.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] Another effective proxy for cosine distance can be obtained by $L_{2}$ normalisation of the vectors, followed by the application of normal Euclidean distance.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] Using this technique each term in each vector is first divided by the magnitude of the vector, yielding a vector of unit length.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] Once the normalisation has occurred, the vector space can be used with the full range of techniques available to any Euclidean space, notably standard dimensionality reduction techniques.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] This normalised form distance is often used within many deep learning algorithms.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] Here, A and B are sets, and $|A|$ is the number of elements in A .
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] If sets are represented as bit vectors, the Otsuka–Ochiai coefficient can be seen to be the same as the cosine similarity.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] It is identical to the score introduced by Godfrey Thomson.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] In a recent book, the coefficient is tentatively misattributed to another Japanese researcher with the family name Otsuka.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] The confusion arises because in 1957 Akira Ochiai attributes the coefficient only to Otsuka (no first name mentioned) by citing an article by Ikuso Hamai (Japanese: 浜井 生三), who in turn cites the original 1936 article by Yanosuke Otsuka.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] The most noteworthy property of cosine similarity is that it reflects a relative, rather than absolute, comparison of the individual vector dimensions.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] For any positive constant a and vector V , the vectors V and $aV$ are maximally similar.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] The measure is thus most appropriate for data where frequency is more important than absolute values; notably, term frequency in documents.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] However more recent metrics with a grounding in information theory, such as Jensen–Shannon, SED, and triangular divergence have been shown to have improved semantics in at least some contexts.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] Cosine similarity is related to Euclidean distance as follows.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] The Euclidean distance is called the *chord distance* (because it is the length of the chord on the unit circle) and it is the Euclidean distance between the vectors which were normalized to unit sum of squared values within them.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] This form of the triangle inequality can be used to bound the minimum and maximum similarity of two objects A and B if the similarities to a reference object C is already known.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] This is used for example in metric data indexing, but has also been used to accelerate spherical k-means clustering the same way the Euclidean triangle inequality has been used to accelerate regular k-means.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] A soft cosine or ("soft" similarity) between two vectors considers similarities between pairs of features.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] For example, in the field of natural language processing (NLP) the similarity among features is quite intuitive.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] Features such as words, *n*-grams, or syntactic *n*-grams can be quite similar, though formally they are considered as different features in the VSM.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] For example, words "play" and "game" are different words and thus mapped to different points in VSM; yet they are semantically related.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] In case of *n*-grams or syntactic *n*-grams, Levenshtein distance can be applied (in fact, Levenshtein distance can be applied to words as well).
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] For calculating soft cosine, the matrix **s** is used to indicate similarity between features.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] It can be calculated through Levenshtein distance, WordNet similarity, or other similarity measures.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] where *sij* = similarity(feature*i*, feature*j*).
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] If there is no similarity between features (*sii* = 1, *sij* = 0 for *i* ≠ *j*), the given equation is equivalent to the conventional cosine similarity formula.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] The time complexity of this measure is quadratic, which makes it applicable to real-world tasks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] Note that the complexity can be reduced to subquadratic.
[src:face-recognition-cv/cosine-similarity] An efficient implementation of such soft cosine similarity is included in the Gensim open source library.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] A **facial recognition system** is a technology potentially capable of matching a human face from a digital image or a video frame against a database of faces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Such a system is typically employed to authenticate users through ID verification services, and works by pinpointing and measuring facial features from a given image.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Development on similar systems began in the 1960s as a form of computer application.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Since their inception, facial recognition systems have seen wider uses in recent times on smartphones and in other forms of technology, such as robotics.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Because computerized facial recognition involves the measurement of a human's physiological characteristics, facial recognition systems are categorized as biometrics.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Although the accuracy of facial recognition systems as a biometric technology is lower than iris recognition, fingerprint image acquisition, palm recognition or voice recognition, it is widely adopted due to its contactless process.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Facial recognition systems have been deployed in advanced human–computer interaction, video surveillance, law enforcement, passenger screening, decisions on employment and housing, and automatic indexing of images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Facial recognition systems are employed throughout the world today by governments and private companies.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Their effectiveness varies, and some systems have previously been scrapped because of their ineffectiveness.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The use of facial recognition systems has also raised controversy, with claims that the systems violate citizens' privacy, commonly make incorrect identifications, encourage gender norms and racial profiling, and do not protect important biometric data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The appearance of synthetic media such as deepfakes has also raised concerns about its security.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] These claims have led to the ban of facial recognition systems in several cities in the United States.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Growing societal concerns led social networking company Meta Platforms to shut down its Facebook facial recognition system in 2021, deleting the face-scan data of more than one billion users.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The change represented one of the largest shifts in facial recognition usage in the technology's history.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] IBM also stopped offering facial recognition technology due to similar concerns.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Automated facial recognition was pioneered in the 1960s by Woody Bledsoe, Helen Chan Wolf, and Charles Bisson, whose work focused on teaching computers to recognize human faces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Their early facial recognition project was dubbed "man-machine" because a human first needed to establish the coordinates of facial features in a photograph before they could be used by a computer for recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Using a graphics tablet, a human would pinpoint facial features coordinates, such as the pupil centers, the inside and outside corners of eyes, and the widows peak in the hairline.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The coordinates were used to calculate 20 individual distances, including the width of the mouth and of the eyes.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] A human could process about 40 pictures an hour, building a database of these computed distances.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] A computer would then automatically compare the distances for each photograph, calculate the difference between the distances, and return the closed records as a possible match.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 1970, Takeo Kanade publicly demonstrated a face-matching system that located anatomical features such as the chin and calculated the distance ratio between facial features without human intervention.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Later tests revealed that the system could not always reliably identify facial features.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Nonetheless, interest in the subject grew and in 1977 Kanade published the first detailed book on facial recognition technology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The FERET tests found that while the performance of existing automated facial recognition systems varied, a handful of existing methods could viably be used to recognize faces in still images taken in a controlled environment.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The FERET tests spawned three US companies that sold automated facial recognition systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Vision Corporation and Miros Inc were founded in 1994, by researchers who used the results of the FERET tests as a selling point.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Viisage Technology was established by an identification card defense contractor in 1996 to commercially exploit the rights to the facial recognition algorithm developed by Alex Pentland at MIT.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Following the 1993 FERET face-recognition vendor test, the Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV) offices in West Virginia and New Mexico became the first DMV offices to use automated facial recognition systems to prevent people from obtaining multiple driving licenses using different names.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Driver's licenses in the United States were at that point a commonly accepted form of photo identification.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] DMV offices across the United States were undergoing a technological upgrade and were in the process of establishing databases of digital ID photographs.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] This enabled DMV offices to deploy the facial recognition systems on the market to search photographs for new driving licenses against the existing DMV database.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] DMV offices became one of the first major markets for automated facial recognition technology and introduced US citizens to facial recognition as a standard method of identification.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The increase of the US prison population in the 1990s prompted U.S. states to established connected and automated identification systems that incorporated digital biometric databases, in some instances this included facial recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 1999, Minnesota incorporated the facial recognition system FaceIT by Visionics into a mug shot booking system that allowed police, judges and court officers to track criminals across the state.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Until the 1990s, facial recognition systems were developed primarily by using photographic portraits of human faces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Research on face recognition to reliably locate a face in an image that contains other objects gained traction in the early 1990s with the principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The PCA method of face detection is also known as Eigenface and was developed by Matthew Turk and Alex Pentland.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Turk and Pentland combined the conceptual approach of the Karhunen–Loève theorem and factor analysis, to develop a linear model.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Eigenfaces are determined based on global and orthogonal features in human faces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] A human face is calculated as a weighted combination of a number of Eigenfaces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Because few Eigenfaces were used to encode human faces of a given population, Turk and Pentland's PCA face detection method greatly reduced the amount of data that had to be processed to detect a face.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Pentland in 1994 defined Eigenface features, including eigen eyes, eigen mouths and eigen noses, to advance the use of PCA in facial recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 1997, the PCA Eigenface method of face recognition was improved upon using linear discriminant analysis (LDA) to produce Fisherfaces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] LDA Fisherfaces became dominantly used in PCA feature based face recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] While Eigenfaces were also used for face reconstruction.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In these approaches no global structure of the face is calculated which links the facial features or parts.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Purely feature based approaches to facial recognition were overtaken in the late 1990s by the Bochum system, which used Gabor filter to record the face features and computed a grid of the face structure to link the features.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Christoph von der Malsburg and his research team at the University of Bochum developed Elastic Bunch Graph Matching in the mid-1990s to extract a face out of an image using skin segmentation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] By 1997, the face detection method developed by Malsburg outperformed most other facial detection systems on the market.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The so-called "Bochum system" of face detection was sold commercially on the market as ZN-Face to operators of airports and other busy locations.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The software was "robust enough to make identifications from less-than-perfect face views.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] It can also often see through such impediments to identification as mustaches, beards, changed hairstyles and glasses—even sunglasses".
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Real-time face detection in video footage became possible in 2001 with the Viola–Jones object detection framework for faces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Paul Viola and Michael Jones combined their face detection method with the Haar-like feature approach to object recognition in digital images to launch AdaBoost, the first real-time frontal-view face detector.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] By 2015, the Viola–Jones algorithm had been implemented using small low power detectors on handheld devices and embedded systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Therefore, the Viola–Jones algorithm has not only broadened the practical application of face recognition systems but has also been used to support new features in user interfaces and teleconferencing.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Ukraine is using the US-based Clearview AI facial recognition software to identify dead Russian soldiers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Ukraine has conducted 8,600 searches and identified the families of 582 deceased Russian soldiers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The IT volunteer section of the Ukrainian army using the software is subsequently contacting the families of the deceased soldiers to raise awareness of Russian activities in Ukraine.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The main goal is to destabilise the Russian government.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] It can be seen as a form of psychological warfare.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] About 340 Ukrainian government officials in five government ministries are using the technology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] It is used to catch spies that might try to enter Ukraine.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Clearview AI's facial recognition database is only available to government agencies who may only use the technology to assist in the course of law enforcement investigations or in connection with national security.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The software was donated to Ukraine by Clearview AI.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Russia is thought to be using it to find anti-war activists.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Clearview AI was originally designed for US law enforcement.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Using it in war raises new ethical concerns.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] One London based surveillance expert, Stephen Hare, is concerned it might make the Ukrainians appear inhuman: "Is it actually working?
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] While humans can recognize faces without much effort, facial recognition is a challenging pattern recognition problem in computing.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Facial recognition systems attempt to identify a human face, which is three-dimensional and changes in appearance with lighting and facial expression, based on its two-dimensional image.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] To accomplish this computational task, facial recognition systems perform four steps.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] First face detection is used to segment the face from the image background.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In the second step the segmented face image is aligned to account for face pose, image size and photographic properties, such as illumination and grayscale.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The purpose of the alignment process is to enable the accurate localization of facial features in the third step, the facial feature extraction.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Features such as eyes, nose and mouth are pinpointed and measured in the image to represent the face.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The so established feature vector of the face is then, in the fourth step, matched against a database of faces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Some face recognition algorithms identify facial features by extracting landmarks, or features, from an image of the subject's face.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] For example, an algorithm may analyze the relative position, size, and/or shape of the eyes, nose, cheekbones, and jaw.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] These features are then used to search for other images with matching features.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Other algorithms normalize a gallery of face images and then compress the face data, only saving the data in the image that is useful for face recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] A probe image is then compared with the face data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] One of the earliest successful systems is based on template matching techniques applied to a set of salient facial features, providing a sort of compressed face representation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Recognition algorithms can be divided into two main approaches: geometric, which looks at distinguishing features, or photo-metric, which is a statistical approach that distills an image into values and compares the values with templates to eliminate variances.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Some classify these algorithms into two broad categories: holistic and feature-based models.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The former attempts to recognize the face in its entirety while the feature-based subdivide into components such as according to features and analyze each as well as its spatial location with respect to other features.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Modern facial recognition systems make increasing use of machine learning techniques such as deep learning.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] To enable human identification at a distance (HID) low-resolution images of faces are enhanced using face hallucination.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In CCTV imagery faces are often very small.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] But because facial recognition algorithms that identify and plot facial features require high resolution images, resolution enhancement techniques have been developed to enable facial recognition systems to work with imagery that has been captured in environments with a high signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Use of face hallucination techniques improves the performance of high resolution facial recognition algorithms and may be used to overcome the inherent limitations of super-resolution algorithms.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Face hallucination techniques are also used to pre-treat imagery where faces are disguised.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Here the disguise, such as sunglasses, is removed and the face hallucination algorithm is applied to the image.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Such face hallucination algorithms need to be trained on similar face images with and without disguise.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] To fill in the area uncovered by removing the disguise, face hallucination algorithms need to correctly map the entire state of the face, which may be not possible due to the momentary facial expression captured in the low resolution image.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Three-dimensional face recognition technique uses 3D sensors to capture information about the shape of a face.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] This information is then used to identify distinctive features on the surface of a face, such as the contour of the eye sockets, nose, and chin.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] One advantage of 3D face recognition is that it is not affected by changes in lighting like other techniques.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] It can also identify a face from a range of viewing angles, including a profile view.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Three-dimensional data points from a face vastly improve the precision of face recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] 3D-dimensional face recognition research is enabled by the development of sophisticated sensors that project structured light onto the face.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] 3D matching technique are sensitive to expressions, therefore researchers at Technion applied tools from metric geometry to treat expressions as isometries.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] A new method of capturing 3D images of faces uses three tracking cameras that point at different angles; one camera will be pointing at the front of the subject, second one to the side, and third one at an angle.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] All these cameras will work together so it can track a subject's face in real-time and be able to face detect and recognize.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] A different form of taking input data for face recognition is by using thermal cameras, by this procedure the cameras will only detect the shape of the head and it will ignore the subject accessories such as glasses, hats, or makeup.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Unlike conventional cameras, thermal cameras can capture facial imagery even in low-light and nighttime conditions without using a flash and exposing the position of the camera.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] However, the databases for face recognition are limited.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Efforts to build databases of thermal face images date back to 2004.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] By 2016, several databases existed, including the IIITD-PSE and the Notre Dame thermal face database.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Current thermal face recognition systems are not able to reliably detect a face in a thermal image that has been taken of an outdoor environment.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) developed a technique that would allow them to match facial imagery obtained using a thermal camera with those in databases that were captured using a conventional camera.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Known as a cross-spectrum synthesis method due to how it bridges facial recognition from two different imaging modalities, this method synthesize a single image by analyzing multiple facial regions and details.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] It consists of a non-linear regression model that maps a specific thermal image into a corresponding visible facial image and an optimization issue that projects the latent projection back into the image space.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] ARL scientists have noted that the approach works by combining global information (i.e. features across the entire face) with local information (i.e. features regarding the eyes, nose, and mouth).
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] According to performance tests conducted at ARL, the multi-region cross-spectrum synthesis model demonstrated a performance improvement of about 30% over baseline methods and about 5% over state-of-the-art methods.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Founded in 2013, Looksery went on to raise money for its face modification app on Kickstarter.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] After successful crowdfunding, Looksery launched in October 2014.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The application allows video chat with others through a special filter for faces that modifies the look of users.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Image augmenting applications already on the market, such as Facetune and Perfect365, were limited to static images, whereas Looksery allowed augmented reality to live videos.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In late 2015 SnapChat purchased Looksery, which would then become its landmark lenses function.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Snapchat filter applications use face detection technology and on the basis of the facial features identified in an image a 3D mesh mask is layered over the face.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] A variety of technologies attempt to fool facial recognition software by the use of anti-facial recognition masks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] DeepFace is a deep learning facial recognition system created by a research group at Facebook.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] It identifies human faces in digital images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] It employs a nine-layer neural net with over 120 million connection weights, and was trained on four million images uploaded by Facebook users.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The system is said to be 97% accurate, compared to 85% for the FBI's Next Generation Identification system.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] TikTok's algorithm has been regarded as especially effective, but many were left to wonder at the exact programming that caused the app to be so effective in guessing the user's desired content.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In June 2020, TikTok released a statement regarding the "For You" page, and how they recommended videos to users, which did not include facial recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In February 2021, however, TikTok agreed to a $92 million settlement to a US lawsuit which alleged that the app had used facial recognition in both user videos and its algorithm to identify age, gender and ethnicity.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The emerging use of facial recognition is in the use of ID verification services.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Many companies and others are working in the market now to provide these services to banks, ICOs, and other e-businesses.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2017, Apple's iPhone X smartphone introduced facial recognition to the product line with its "Face ID" platform, which uses an infrared illumination system.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Apple introduced Face ID on the flagship iPhone X as a biometric authentication successor to the Touch ID, a fingerprint based system.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Face ID has a facial recognition sensor that consists of two parts: a "Romeo" module that projects more than 30,000 infrared dots onto the user's face, and a "Juliet" module that reads the pattern.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The pattern is sent to a local "Secure Enclave" in the device's central processing unit (CPU) to confirm a match with the phone owner's face.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The facial pattern is not accessible by Apple.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The system will not work with eyes closed, in an effort to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The technology learns from changes in a user's appearance, and therefore works with hats, scarves, glasses, and many sunglasses, beard and makeup.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] This is done by using a "Flood Illuminator", which is a dedicated infrared flash that throws out invisible infrared light onto the user's face to get a 2d picture in addition to the 30,000 facial points.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Facial recognition algorithms can help in diagnosing some diseases using specific features on the nose, cheeks and other part of the human face.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Relying on developed data sets, machine learning has been used to identify genetic abnormalities just based on facial dimensions.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] FRT has also been used to verify patients before surgery procedures.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In March, 2022 according to a publication by Forbes, FDNA, an AI development company claimed that in the space of 10 years, they have worked with geneticists to develop a database of about 5,000 diseases and 1500 of them can be detected with facial recognition algorithms.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In an interview, the National Health Authority chief Dr.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Sharma said that facial recognition technology would be used in conjunction with Aadhaar to authenticate the identity of people seeking vaccines.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Ten human rights and digital rights organizations and more than 150 individuals signed a statement by the Internet Freedom Foundation that raised alarm against the deployment of facial recognition technology in the central government's vaccination drive process.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Implementation of an error-prone system without adequate legislation containing mandatory safeguards, would deprive citizens of essential services and linking this untested technology to the vaccination roll-out in India will only exclude persons from the vaccine delivery system.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In July, 2021, a press release by the Government of Meghalaya stated that facial recognition technology (FRT) would be used to verify the identity of pensioners to issue a Digital Life Certificate using "Pensioner's Life Certification Verification" mobile application.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The notice, according to the press release, purports to offer pensioners "a secure, easy and hassle-free interface for verifying their liveness to the Pension Disbursing Authorities from the comfort of their homes using smart phones".
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Australian Border Force and New Zealand Customs Service have set up an automated border processing system called SmartGate that uses face recognition, which compares the face of the traveller with the data in the e-passport microchip.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] All Canadian international airports use facial recognition as part of the Primary Inspection Kiosk program that compares a traveler face to their photo stored on the ePassport.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] This program first came to Vancouver International Airport in early 2017 and was rolled up to all remaining international airports in 2018–2019.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Police forces in the United Kingdom have been trialing live facial recognition technology at public events since 2015.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In May 2017, a man was arrested using an automatic facial recognition (AFR) system mounted on a van operated by the South Wales Police.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Ars Technica reported that "this appears to be the first time [AFR] has led to an arrest".
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] However, a 2018 report by Big Brother Watch found that these systems were up to 98% inaccurate.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The report also revealed that two UK police forces, South Wales Police and the Metropolitan Police, were using live facial recognition at public events and in public spaces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In September 2019, South Wales Police use of facial recognition was ruled lawful.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Live facial recognition has been trialled since 2016 in the streets of London and will be used on a regular basis from Metropolitan Police from beginning of 2020.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In August 2020 the Court of Appeal ruled that the way the facial recognition system had been used by the South Wales Police in 2017 and 2018 violated human rights.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] However, by 2024 the Metropolitan Police were using the technique with a database of 16,000 suspects, leading to over 360 arrests, including rapists and someone wanted for grievous bodily harm for 8 years.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] They claim a false positive rate of only 1 in 6,000.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The photos of those not identified by the system are deleted immediately.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Department of State operates one of the largest face recognition systems in the world with a database of 117 million American adults, with photos typically drawn from driver's license photos.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Although it is still far from completion, it is being put to use in certain cities to give clues as to who was in the photo.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The FBI uses the photos as an investigative tool, not for positive identification.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] As of 2016, facial recognition was being used to identify people in photos taken by police in San Diego and Los Angeles (not on real-time video, and only against booking photos) and use was planned in West Virginia and Dallas.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In recent years Maryland has used face recognition by comparing people's faces to their driver's license photos.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The system drew controversy when it was used in Baltimore to arrest unruly protesters after the death of Freddie Gray in police custody.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Many other states are using or developing a similar system however some states have laws prohibiting its use.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The FBI has also instituted its Next Generation Identification program to include face recognition, as well as more traditional biometrics like fingerprints and iris scans, which can pull from both criminal and civil databases.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The federal Government Accountability Office criticized the FBI for not addressing various concerns related to privacy and accuracy.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Customs and Border Protection deployed "biometric face scanners" at U.S. airports.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Passengers taking outbound international flights can complete the check-in, security and the boarding process after getting facial images captured and verified by matching their ID photos stored on CBP's database.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Images captured for travelers with U.S. citizenship will be deleted within up to 12-hours.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Transportation Security Administration (TSA) had expressed its intention to adopt a similar program for domestic air travel during the security check process in the future.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The American Civil Liberties Union is one of the organizations against the program, concerning that the program will be used for surveillance purposes.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2019, researchers reported that Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) uses facial recognition software against state driver's license databases, including for some states that provide licenses to undocumented immigrants.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In December 2022, 16 major domestic airports in the US started testing facial-recognition tech where kiosks with cameras are checking the photos on travelers' IDs to make sure that passengers are not impostors.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2006, the "Skynet" (天網) Project was initiated by the Chinese government to implement CCTV surveillance nationwide and as of 2018, there have been 20 million cameras, many of which are capable of real-time facial recognition, deployed across the country for this project.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Some official claim that the current Skynet system can scan the entire Chinese population in one second and the world population in two seconds.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2017, the Qingdao police was able to identify twenty-five wanted suspects using facial recognition equipment at the Qingdao International Beer Festival, one of which had been on the run for 10 years.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The equipment works by recording a 15-second video clip and taking multiple snapshots of the subject.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] That data is compared and analyzed with images from the police department's database and within 20 minutes, the subject can be identified with a 98.1% accuracy.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2018, Chinese police in Zhengzhou and Beijing were using smart glasses to take photos which are compared against a government database using facial recognition to identify suspects, retrieve an address, and track people moving beyond their home areas.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] As of late 2017, China has deployed facial recognition and artificial intelligence technology in Xinjiang.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Reporters visiting the region found surveillance cameras installed every hundred meters or so in several cities, as well as facial recognition checkpoints at areas like gas stations, shopping centers, and mosque entrances.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In May 2019, Human Rights Watch reported finding Face++ code in the Integrated Joint Operations Platform (IJOP), a police surveillance app used to collect data on, and track the Uighur community in Xinjiang.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Human Rights Watch released a correction to its report in June 2019 stating that the Chinese company Megvii did not appear to have collaborated on IJOP, and that the Face++ code in the app was inoperable.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In February 2020, following the Coronavirus outbreak, Megvii applied for a bank loan to optimize the body temperature screening system it had launched to help identify people with symptoms of a Coronavirus infection in crowds.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In its loan application documents, Megvii stated that it needed to improve the accuracy of identifying masked individuals.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Many public places in China are implemented with facial recognition equipment, including railway stations, airports, tourist attractions, expos, and office buildings.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In October 2019, a professor at Zhejiang Sci-Tech University sued the Hangzhou Safari Park for abusing private biometric information of customers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The safari park uses facial recognition technology to verify the identities of its Year Card holders.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] An estimated 300 tourist sites in China have installed facial recognition systems and use them to admit visitors.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] This case is reported to be the first on the use of facial recognition systems in China.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In August 2020, Radio Free Asia reported that in 2019 Geng Guanjun, a citizen of Taiyuan City who had used the WeChat app by Tencent to forward a video to a friend in the United States was subsequently convicted on the charge of the crime "picking quarrels and provoking troubles".
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Court documents showed that the Chinese police used a facial recognition system to identify Geng Guanjun as an "overseas democracy activist" and that China's network management and propaganda departments directly monitor WeChat users.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2019, Protestors in Hong Kong destroyed smart lampposts amid concerns they could contain cameras and facial recognition system used for surveillance by Chinese authorities.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Human rights groups have criticized the Chinese government for using artificial intelligence facial recognition technology in its suppression against Uyghurs, Christians and Falun Gong practitioners.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Even though facial recognition technology (FRT) is not fully accurate, it is being increasingly deployed for identification purposes by the police in India.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] FRT systems generate a probability match score, or a confidence score between the suspect who is to be identified and the database of identified criminals that is available with the police.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The National Automated Facial Recognition System (AFRS) is already being developed by the National Crime Records Bureau (NCRB), a body constituted under the Ministry of Home Affairs.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The project seeks to develop and deploy a national database of photographs which would comport with a facial recognition technology system by the central and state security agencies.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Internet Freedom Foundation has flagged concerns regarding the project.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The NGO has highlighted that the accuracy of FRT systems are "routinely exaggerated and the real numbers leave much to be desired.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Under the Supreme Court of India's decision in *Justice K.S.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Crime and Criminal Tracking Network and Systems (CCTNS), which is a Mission Mode Project under the National e-Governance Plan (NeGP), is viewed as a system which would connect police stations across India, and help them "talk" to each other.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The project's objective is to digitize all FIR-related information, including FIRs registered, as well as cases investigated, charge sheets filed, and suspects and wanted persons in all police stations.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] This shall constitute a national database of crime and criminals in India.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] CCTNS is being implemented without a data protection law in place.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] CCTNS is proposed to be integrated with the AFRS, a repository of all crime and criminal related facial data which can be deployed to purportedly identify or verify a person from a variety of inputs ranging from images to videos.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] This has raised privacy concerns from civil society organizations and privacy experts.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Both the projects have been censured as instruments of "mass surveillance" at the hands of the state.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In Rajasthan, 'RajCop,' a police app has been recently integrated with a facial recognition module which can match the face of a suspect against a database of known persons in real-time.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The state of Telangana has installed 8 lakh CCTV cameras, with its capital city Hyderabad slowly turning into a surveillance capital.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] A false positive happens when facial recognition technology misidentifies a person to be someone they are not, that is, it yields an incorrect positive result.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] They often results in discrimination and strengthening of existing biases.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] For example, in 2018, Delhi Police reported that its FRT system had an accuracy rate of 2%, which sank to 1% in 2019.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The FRT system even failed to distinguish accurately between different sexes.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The government of Delhi in collaboration with Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) is developing a new technology called Crime Mapping Analytics and Predictive System (CMAPS).
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The project aims to deploy space technology for "controlling crime and maintaining law and order." The system will be connected to a database containing data of criminals.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The technology is envisaged to be deployed to collect real-time data at the crime scene.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] A Right to Information (RTI) request dated July 30, 2020 was filed with the Office of the Commissioner, Kolkata Police, seeking information about the facial recognition technology that the department was using.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The information sought was denied stating that the department was exempted from disclosure under section 24(4) of the RTI Act.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In the 2000 Mexican presidential election, the Mexican government employed face recognition software to prevent voter fraud.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Some individuals had been registering to vote under several different names, in an attempt to place multiple votes.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] By comparing new face images to those already in the voter database, authorities were able to reduce duplicate registrations.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In Colombia public transport busses are fitted with a facial recognition system by FaceFirst Inc to identify passengers that are sought by the National Police of Colombia.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] FaceFirst Inc also built the facial recognition system for Tocumen International Airport in Panama.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The face recognition system is deployed to identify individuals among the travellers that are sought by the Panamanian National Police or Interpol.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Tocumen International Airport operates an airport-wide surveillance system using hundreds of live face recognition cameras to identify wanted individuals passing through the airport.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] At the 2014 FIFA World Cup in Brazil the Federal Police of Brazil used face recognition goggles.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Face recognition systems "made in China" were also deployed at the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Nuctech Company provided 145 inspection terminals for Maracanã Stadium and 55 terminals for the Deodoro Olympic Park.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Police forces in at least 21 countries of the European Union use, or plan to use, facial recognition systems, either for administrative or criminal purposes.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Greek police passed a contract with Intracom-Telecom for the provision of at least 1,000 devices equipped with live facial recognition system.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The delivery is expected before the summer 2021.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The total value of the contract is over 4 million euros, paid for in large part by the Internal Security Fund of the European Commission.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Italian police acquired a face recognition system in 2017, Sistema Automatico Riconoscimento Immagini (SARI).
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In November 2020, the Interior ministry announced plans to use it in real-time to identify people suspected of seeking asylum.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Netherlands has deployed facial recognition and artificial intelligence technology since 2016.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The database of the Dutch police currently contains over 2.2 million pictures of 1.3 million Dutch citizens.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] This accounts for about 8% of the population.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In The Netherlands, face recognition is not used by the police on municipal CCTV.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In South Africa, in 2016, the city of Johannesburg announced it was rolling out smart CCTV cameras complete with automatic number plate recognition and facial recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The US firm 3VR, now Identiv, is an example of a vendor which began offering facial recognition systems and services to retailers as early as 2007.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2018, the National Retail Federation Loss Prevention Research Council called facial recognition technology "a promising new tool" worth evaluating.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In July 2020, the Reuters news agency reported that during the 2010s the pharmacy chain Rite Aid had deployed facial recognition video surveillance systems and components from FaceFirst, DeepCam LLC, and other vendors at some retail locations in the United States.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In a 2020 statement to Reuters in response to the reporting, Rite Aid said that it had ceased using the facial recognition software and switched off the cameras.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] According to director Read Hayes of the National Retail Federation Loss Prevention Research Council, Rite Aid's surveillance program was either the largest or one of the largest programs in retail.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Home Depot, Menards, Walmart, and 7-Eleven are among other US retailers also engaged in large-scale pilot programs or deployments of facial recognition technology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Rite Aid said that the selection of locations was "data-driven", based on the theft histories of individual stores, local and national crime data, and site infrastructure.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2019, facial recognition to prevent theft was in use at Sydney's Star Casino and was also deployed at gaming venues in New Zealand.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In June 2022, consumer group CHOICE reported facial recognition was in use in Australia at Kmart, Bunnings, and The Good Guys.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Good Guys subsequently suspended the technology pending a legal challenge by CHOICE to the Office of the Australian Information Commissioner, while Bunnings kept the technology in use and Kmart maintained its trial of the technology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] At the American football championship game Super Bowl XXXV in January 2001, police in Tampa Bay, Florida used Viisage face recognition software to search for potential criminals and terrorists in attendance at the event.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] 19 people with minor criminal records were potentially identified.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Face recognition systems have also been used by photo management software to identify the subjects of photographs, enabling features such as searching images by person, as well as suggesting photos to be shared with a specific contact if their presence were detected in a photo.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] By 2008 facial recognition systems were typically used as access control in security systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The United States' popular music and country music celebrity Taylor Swift surreptitiously employed facial recognition technology at a concert in 2018.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The camera was embedded in a kiosk near a ticket booth and scanned concert-goers as they entered the facility for known stalkers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] On August 18, 2019, *The Times* reported that the UAE-owned Manchester City hired a Texas-based firm, Blink Identity, to deploy facial recognition systems in a driver program.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The club has planned a single super-fast lane for the supporters at the Etihad stadium.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] However, civil rights groups cautioned the club against the introduction of this technology, saying that it would risk "normalising a mass surveillance tool".
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The policy and campaigns officer at Liberty, Hannah Couchman said that Man City's move is alarming, since the fans will be obliged to share deeply sensitive personal information with a private company, where they could be tracked and monitored in their everyday lives.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2019, casinos in Australia and New Zealand rolled out facial recognition to prevent theft, and a representative of Sydney's Star Casino said they would also provide 'customer service' like welcoming a patron back to a bar.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] In August 2020, amid the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States, American football stadiums of New York and Los Angeles announced the installation of facial recognition for upcoming matches.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] The purpose is to make the entry process as touchless as possible.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p01] Media companies have begun using face recognition technology to streamline their tracking, organizing, and archiving pictures and videos.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In 2006, the performance of the latest face recognition algorithms was evaluated in the Face Recognition Grand Challenge (FRGC).
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] High-resolution face images, 3-D face scans, and iris images were used in the tests.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The results indicated that the new algorithms are 10 times more accurate than the face recognition algorithms of 2002 and 100 times more accurate than those of 1995.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Some of the algorithms were able to outperform human participants in recognizing faces and could uniquely identify identical twins.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] One key advantage of a facial recognition system that it is able to perform mass identification as it does not require the cooperation of the test subject to work.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Properly designed systems installed in airports, multiplexes, and other public places can identify individuals among the crowd, without passers-by even being aware of the system.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] However, as compared to other biometric techniques, face recognition may not be most reliable and efficient.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Quality measures are very important in facial recognition systems as large degrees of variations are possible in face images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Factors such as illumination, expression, pose and noise during face capture can affect the performance of facial recognition systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Among all biometric systems, facial recognition has the highest false acceptance and rejection rates, thus questions have been raised on the effectiveness of or bias of face recognition software in cases of railway and airport security, law enforcement and housing and employment decisions.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] This is one of the main obstacles of face recognition in surveillance systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] It has also been suggested that camera settings can favour sharper imagery of white skin than of other skin tones.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Face recognition is less effective if facial expressions vary.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] A big smile can render the system less effective.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] For instance: Canada, in 2009, allowed only neutral facial expressions in passport photos.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] There is also inconstancy in the datasets used by researchers.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Researchers may use anywhere from several subjects to scores of subjects and a few hundred images to thousands of images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Data sets may be diverse and inclusive or mainly contain images of white males.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] It is important for researchers to make available the datasets they used to each other, or have at least a standard or representative dataset.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Although high degrees of accuracy have been claimed for some facial recognition systems, these outcomes are not universal.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The consistently worst accuracy rate is for those who are 18 to 30 years old, Black and female.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Studies have shown that facial recognition algorithms tend to perform better on individuals with lighter skin tones compared to those with darker skin tones.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] For example, a 2018 study found that leading commercial gender classification models, which are facial recognition models, have an error rate up to 7 times higher for those with darker skin tones compared to those with lighter skin tones.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Initially this disparity was attributed to the imbalance in training datasets, which often overrepresent lighter-skinned individuals, leading to higher error rates for darker-skinned people.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] However, later studies showed that dataset imbalance is not the sole cause for difference in performance.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Common image compression methods, such as JPEG chroma subsampling, have been found to disproportionately degrade performance for darker-skinned individuals.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] These methods inadequately represent color information, which adversely affects the ability of algorithms to recognize darker-skinned individuals accurately.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Facial recognition systems often demonstrate lower accuracy when identifying individuals with non-Eurocentric facial features.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Known as the Cross-race effect, this bias occurs when systems perform better on racial or ethnic groups that are overrepresented in their training data, resulting in reduced accuracy for underrepresented groups.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The overrepresented group is generally the more populous group in the location that the model is being developed.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] For example, models developed in Asian cultures generally perform better on Asian facial features than Eurocentric facial features due to overrepresentation in the developers training dataset.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The opposite is observed in models developed in Eurocentric cultures.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The systems used for facial recognition often lack the sufficient training needed to fully recognize those features not of Eurocentric descent.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] When the training and databases for these Machine Learning (ML) models do not contain a diverse representation, the models fail to identify the missed population, adding to their racial biases.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The cross-race effect is not exclusive to machines; humans also experience difficulty recognizing faces from racial or ethnic groups different from their own.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] This is an example of inherent human biases being perpetuated in training datasets.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Facial recognition technologies encounter significant challenges when identifying individuals with disabilities.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] For instance, systems have been shown to perform worse when recognizing individuals with Down syndrome, often leading to increased false match rates.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] This is due to distinct facial structures associated with the condition that are not adequately represented in training datasets.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] More broadly, facial recognition systems tend to overlook diverse physical characteristics related to disabilities.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The lack of representative data for individuals with varying disabilities further emphasizes the need for inclusive algorithmic designs to mitigate bias and improve accuracy.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Additionally, facial expression recognition technologies often fail to accurately interpret the emotional states of individuals with intellectual disabilities.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] This shortcoming can hinder effective communication and interaction, underscoring the necessity for systems trained on diverse datasets that include individuals with intellectual disabilities.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Furthermore, biases in facial recognition algorithms can lead to discriminatory outcomes for people with disabilities.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] For example, certain facial features or asymmetries may result in misidentification or exclusion, highlighting the importance of developing accessible and fair biometric systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] A review in 2025 showed improved mitigation of demographic biases in face recognition: by processing at input, model, or output stages.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Additionally, targeted dataset collection has been shown to improve racial equity in facial recognition systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] By prioritizing diverse data inputs, researchers demonstrated measurable reductions in performance disparities between racial groups.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Critics of the technology complain that the London Borough of Newham scheme has, as of 2004, never recognized a single criminal, despite several criminals in the system's database living in the Borough and the system has been running for several years.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] "Not once, as far as the police know, has Newham's automatic face recognition system spotted a live target." This information seems to conflict with claims that the system was credited with a 34% reduction in crime (hence why it was rolled out to Birmingham also).
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] An experiment in 2002 by the local police department in Tampa, Florida, had similarly disappointing results.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] A system at Boston's Logan Airport was shut down in 2003 after failing to make any matches during a two-year test period.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In 2014, Facebook stated that in a standardized two-option facial recognition test, its online system scored 97.25% accuracy, compared to the human benchmark of 97.5%.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Systems are often advertised as having accuracy near 100%; this is misleading as the outcomes are not universal.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The studies often use samples that are smaller and less diverse than would be necessary for large scale applications.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Because facial recognition is not completely accurate, it creates a list of potential matches.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] A human operator must then look through these potential matches and studies show the operators pick the correct match out of the list only about half the time.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] This causes the issue of targeting the wrong suspect.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Civil rights organizations and privacy campaigners such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation, Big Brother Watch and the ACLU express concern that privacy is being compromised by the use of surveillance technologies.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Face recognition can be used not just to identify an individual, but also to unearth other personal data associated with an individual – such as other photos featuring the individual, blog posts, social media profiles, Internet behavior, and travel patterns.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Concerns have been raised over who would have access to the knowledge of one's whereabouts and people with them at any given time.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Moreover, individuals have limited ability to avoid or thwart face recognition tracking unless they hide their faces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] This fundamentally changes the dynamic of day-to-day privacy by enabling any marketer, government agency, or random stranger to secretly collect the identities and associated personal information of any individual captured by the face recognition system.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Consumers may not understand or be aware of what their data is being used for, which denies them the ability to consent to how their personal information gets shared.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In July 2015, the United States Government Accountability Office conducted a Report to the Ranking Member, Subcommittee on Privacy, Technology and the Law, Committee on the Judiciary, U.S.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The report discussed facial recognition technology's commercial uses, privacy issues, and the applicable federal law.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] It states that previously, issues concerning facial recognition technology were discussed and represent the need for updating the privacy laws of the United States so that federal law continually matches the impact of advanced technologies.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The report noted that some industry, government, and private organizations were in the process of developing, or have developed, "voluntary privacy guidelines".
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] These guidelines varied between the stakeholders, but their overall aim was to gain consent and inform citizens of the intended use of facial recognition technology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] According to the report the voluntary privacy guidelines helped to counteract the privacy concerns that arise when citizens are unaware of how their personal data gets put to use.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In December 2017, Facebook rolled out a new feature that notifies a user when someone uploads a photo that includes what Facebook thinks is their face, even if they are not tagged.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Facebook has attempted to frame the new functionality in a positive light, amidst prior backlashes.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Facebook's head of privacy, Rob Sherman, addressed this new feature as one that gives people more control over their photos online.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] "We've thought about this as a really empowering feature," he says.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The most recent case was dismissed in January 2016 because the court lacked jurisdiction.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In the US, surveillance companies such as Clearview AI are relying on the First Amendment to the United States Constitution to data scrape user accounts on social media platforms for data that can be used in the development of facial recognition systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In 2019, the *Financial Times* first reported that facial recognition software was in use in the King's Cross area of London.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The development around London's King's Cross mainline station includes shops, offices, Google's UK HQ and part of St Martin's College.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In September 2019 it was announced by Argent that facial recognition software would no longer be used at King's Cross.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Argent claimed that the software had been deployed between May 2016 and March 2018 on two cameras covering a pedestrian street running through the centre of the development.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In October 2019, a report by the deputy London mayor Sophie Linden revealed that in a secret deal the Metropolitan Police had passed photos of seven people to Argent for use in their King's cross facial recognition system.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Automated Facial Recognition was trialled by the South Wales Police on multiple occasions between 2017 and 2019.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The use of the technology was challenged in court by a private individual, Edward Bridges, with support from the charity Liberty (case known as R (Bridges) v Chief Constable South Wales Police).
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The case was heard in the Court of Appeal and a judgement was given in August 2020.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The case argued that the use of Facial Recognition was a privacy violation on the basis that there was insufficient legal framework or proportionality in the use of Facial Recognition and that its use was in violation of the Data Protection Acts 1998 and 2018.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The case was decided in favour of Bridges and did not award damages.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The case was settled via a declaration of wrongdoing.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In response to the case, the British Government has repeatedly attempted to pass a Bill regulating the use of Facial Recognition in public spaces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The proposed Bills have attempted to appoint a Commissioner with the ability to regulate Facial Recognition use by Government Services in a similar manner to the Commissioner for CCTV.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Such a Bill has yet to come into force [correct as of September 2021].
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] She noted such a move would could go against federal, state, and local human rights laws.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] As of 2018, it is still contested as to whether or not facial recognition technology works less accurately on people of color.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] One study by Joy Buolamwini (MIT Media Lab) and Timnit Gebru (Microsoft Research) found that the error rate for gender recognition for women of color within three commercial facial recognition systems ranged from 23.8% to 36%, whereas for lighter-skinned men it was between 0.0 and 1.6%.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Overall accuracy rates for identifying men (91.9%) were higher than for women (79.4%), and none of the systems accommodated a non-binary understanding of gender.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] It also showed that the datasets used to train commercial facial recognition models were unrepresentative of the broader population and skewed toward lighter-skinned males.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] However, another study showed that several commercial facial recognition software sold to law enforcement offices around the country had a lower false non-match rate for black people than for white people.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Experts fear that face recognition systems may actually be hurting citizens the police claims they are trying to protect.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The lack of regulations holding facial recognition technology companies to requirements of racially biased testing can be a significant flaw in the adoption of use in law enforcement.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] CyberExtruder, a company that markets itself to law enforcement said that they had not performed testing or research on bias in their software.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] CyberExtruder did note that some skin colors are more difficult for the software to recognize with current limitations of the technology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] "Just as individuals with very dark skin are hard to identify with high significance via facial recognition, individuals with very pale skin are the same," said Blake Senftner, a senior software engineer at CyberExtruder.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The United States' National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) carried out extensive testing of FRT system 1:1 verification and 1:many identification.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] It also tested for the differing accuracy of FRT across different demographic groups.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The independent study concluded at present, no FRT system has 100% accuracy.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In 2010, Peru passed the Law for Personal Data Protection, which defines biometric information that can be used to identify an individual as sensitive data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In 2012, Colombia passed a comprehensive Data Protection Law which defines biometric data as sensitive information.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] According to Article 9(1) of the EU's 2016 General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) the processing of biometric data for the purpose of "uniquely identifying a natural person" is sensitive and the facial recognition data processed in this way becomes sensitive personal data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In September 2019 the Swedish Data Protection Authority (DPA) issued its first ever financial penalty for a violation of the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) against a school that was using the technology to replace time-consuming roll calls during class.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The DPA found that the school illegally obtained the biometric data of its students without completing an impact assessment.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In addition the school did not make the DPA aware of the pilot scheme.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In the United States of America several U.S. states have passed laws to protect the privacy of biometric data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Examples include the Illinois Biometric Information Privacy Act (BIPA) and the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA).
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In March 2020 California residents filed a class action against Clearview AI, alleging that the company had illegally collected biometric data online and with the help of face recognition technology built up a database of biometric data which was sold to companies and police forces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] At the time Clearview AI already faced two lawsuits under BIPA and an investigation by the Privacy Commissioner of Canada for compliance with the Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act (PIPEDA).
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In May 2019, San Francisco, California became the first major United States city to ban the use of facial recognition software for police and other local government agencies' usage.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] San Francisco Supervisor, Aaron Peskin, introduced regulations that will require agencies to gain approval from the San Francisco Board of Supervisors to purchase surveillance technology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The regulations also require that agencies publicly disclose the intended use for new surveillance technology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In June 2019, Somerville, Massachusetts became the first city on the East Coast to ban face surveillance software for government use, specifically in police investigations and municipal surveillance.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In July 2019, Oakland, California banned the usage of facial recognition technology by city departments.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The American Civil Liberties Union ("ACLU") has campaigned across the United States for transparency in surveillance technology and has supported both San Francisco and Somerville's ban on facial recognition software.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The ACLU works to challenge the secrecy and surveillance with this technology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] During the George Floyd protests, use of facial recognition by city government was banned in Boston, Massachusetts.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The West Lafayette, Indiana City Council passed an ordinance banning facial recognition surveillance technology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] On October 27, 2020, 22 human rights groups called upon the University of Miami to ban facial recognition technology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] This came after the students accused the school of using the software to identify student protesters.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The allegations were, however, denied by the university.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] A state police reform law in Massachusetts will take effect in July 2021; a ban passed by the legislature was rejected by governor Charlie Baker.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Instead, the law requires a judicial warrant, limit the personnel who can perform the search, record data about how the technology is used, and create a commission to make recommendations about future regulations.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Reports in 2024 revealed that some police departments, including San Francisco Police Department, had skirted bans on facial recognition technology that had been enacted in their respective cities.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In January 2020, the European Union suggested, but then quickly scrapped, a proposed moratorium on facial recognition in public spaces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The European "Reclaim Your Face" coalition launched in October 2020.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The coalition calls for a ban on facial recognition and launched a European Citizens' Initiative in February 2021.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] More than 60 organizations call on the European Commission to strictly regulate the use of biometric surveillance technologies.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In the 18th and 19th century, the belief that facial expressions revealed the moral worth or true inner state of a human was widespread and physiognomy was a respected science in the Western world.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] From the early 19th century onwards photography was used in the physiognomic analysis of facial features and facial expression to detect insanity and dementia.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In the 1960s and 1970s the study of human emotions and its expressions was reinvented by psychologists, who tried to define a normal range of emotional responses to events.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The research on automated emotion recognition has since the 1970s focused on facial expressions and speech, which are regarded as the two most important ways in which humans communicate emotions to other humans.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In the 1970s the Facial Action Coding System (FACS) categorization for the physical expression of emotions was established.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Its developer Paul Ekman maintains that there are six emotions that are universal to all human beings and that these can be coded in facial expressions.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Research into automatic emotion specific expression recognition has in the past decades focused on frontal view images of human faces.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Facial thermography can be considered as a promising tool of emotion recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In 2016, facial feature emotion recognition algorithms were among the new technologies, alongside high-definition CCTV, high resolution 3D face recognition and iris recognition, that found their way out of university research labs.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In 2016, Facebook acquired FacioMetrics, a facial feature emotion recognition corporate spin-off by Carnegie Mellon University.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In the same year Apple Inc. acquired the facial feature emotion recognition start-up Emotient.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] By the end of 2016, commercial vendors of facial recognition systems offered to integrate and deploy emotion recognition algorithms for facial features.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The MIT's Media Lab spin-off Affectiva by late 2019 offered a facial expression emotion detection product that can recognize emotions in humans while driving.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The development of anti-facial recognition technology is effectively an arms race between privacy researchers and big data companies.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Big data companies increasingly use convolutional AI technology to create ever more advanced facial recognition models.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Solutions to block facial recognition may not work on newer software, or on different types of facial recognition models.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] One popular cited example of facial-recognition blocking is the CVDazzle makeup and haircut system, but the creators note on their website that it has been outdated for quite some time as it was designed to combat a particular facial recognition algorithm and may not work.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Another example is the emergence of facial recognition that can identify people wearing facemasks and sunglasses, especially after the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Given that big data companies have much more funding than privacy researchers, it is very difficult for anti-facial recognition systems to keep up.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] There is also no guarantee that obfuscation techniques that were used for images taken in the past and stored, such as masks or software obfuscation, would protect users from facial-recognition analysis of those images by future technology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] In January 2013, Japanese researchers from the National Institute of Informatics created 'privacy visor' glasses that use nearly infrared light to make the face underneath it unrecognizable to face recognition software that use infrared.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The latest version uses a titanium frame, light-reflective material and a mask which uses angles and patterns to disrupt facial recognition technology through both absorbing and bouncing back light sources.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] However, these methods are used to prevent infrared facial recognition and would not work on AI facial recognition of plain images.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Some projects use adversarial machine learning to come up with new printed patterns that confuse existing face recognition software.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] One method that may work to protect from facial recognition systems are specific haircuts and make-up patterns that prevent the used algorithms to detect a face, known as computer vision dazzle.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Incidentally, the makeup styles popular with Juggalos may also protect against facial recognition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Facial masks that are worn to protect from contagious viruses can reduce the accuracy of facial recognition systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] A 2020 NIST study, tested popular one-to-one matching systems and found a failure rate between five and fifty percent on masked individuals.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] *The Verge* speculated that the accuracy rate of mass surveillance systems, which were not included in the study, would be even less accurate than the accuracy of one-to-one matching systems.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] The facial recognition of Apple Pay can work through many barriers, including heavy makeup, thick beards and even sunglasses, but fails with masks.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] However, facial recognition of masked faces is increasingly getting more reliable.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Another solution is the application of obfuscation to images that may fool facial recognition systems while still appearing normal to a human user.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] These could be used for when images are posted online or on social media.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] However, as it is hard to remove images once they are on the internet, the obfuscation on these images may be defeated and the face of the user identified by future advances in technology.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] Two examples of this technique, developed in 2020, are the ANU's 'Camera Adversaria' camera app, and the University of Chicago's Fawkes image cloaking software algorithm which applies obfuscation to already taken photos.
[src:face-recognition-cv/facial-recognition-system-p02] However, by 2021 the Fawkes obfuscation algorithm had already been specifically targeted by Microsoft Azure which changed its algorithm to lower Fawkes' effectiveness.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Beyond machine learning, the principles of feature engineering are applied in various scientific fields, including physics.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] For example, physicists construct dimensionless numbers such as the Reynolds number in fluid dynamics, the Nusselt number in heat transfer, and the Archimedes number in sedimentation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] They also develop first approximations of solutions, such as analytical solutions for the strength of materials in mechanics.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] One of the applications of feature engineering has been clustering of feature-objects or sample-objects in a dataset.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Especially, feature engineering based on matrix decomposition has been extensively used for data clustering under non-negativity constraints on the feature coefficients.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] These include *Non-Negative Matrix Factorization* (NMF), *Non-Negative Matrix-Tri Factorization* (NMTF), *Non-Negative Tensor Decomposition/Factorization* (NTF/NTD), etc.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] The non-negativity constraints on coefficients of the feature vectors mined by the above-stated algorithms yields a part-based representation, and different factor matrices exhibit natural clustering properties.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Several extensions of the above-stated feature engineering methods have been reported in literature, including *orthogonality-constrained factorization* for hard clustering, and *manifold learning* to overcome inherent issues with these algorithms.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Other classes of feature engineering algorithms include leveraging a common hidden structure across multiple inter-related datasets to obtain a consensus (common) clustering scheme.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] An example is *Multi-view Classification based on Consensus Matrix Decomposition* (MCMD), which mines a common clustering scheme across multiple datasets.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Coupled matrix and tensor decompositions are popular in multi-view feature engineering.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Feature engineering in machine learning and statistical modeling involves selecting, creating, transforming, and extracting data features.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Even relatively insignificant features may contribute to a model.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Feature selection can reduce the number of features to prevent a model from becoming too specific to the training data set (overfitting).
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Feature explosion occurs when the number of identified features is too large for effective model estimation or optimization.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Feature explosion can be limited via techniques such as regularization, kernel methods, and feature selection.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Automation of feature engineering is a research topic that dates back to the 1990s.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Machine learning software that incorporates automated feature engineering has been commercially available since 2016.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Multi-relational Decision Tree Learning (MRDTL) extends traditional decision tree methods to relational databases, handling complex data relationships across tables.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] It innovatively uses selection graphs as decision nodes, refined systematically until a specific termination criterion is reached.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Most MRDTL studies base implementations on relational databases, which results in many redundant operations.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] These redundancies can be reduced by using techniques such as tuple id propagation.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] The deep feature synthesis (DFS) algorithm beat 615 of 906 human teams in a competition.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] The feature store is where the features are stored and organized for the explicit purpose of being used to either train models (by data scientists) or make predictions (by applications that have a trained model).
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] A feature store includes the ability to store code used to generate features, apply the code to raw data, and serve those features to models upon request.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Useful capabilities include feature versioning and policies governing the circumstances under which features can be used.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Feature stores can be standalone software tools or built into machine learning platforms.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Feature engineering can be a time-consuming and error-prone process, as it requires domain expertise and often involves trial and error.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] Deep learning algorithms may be used to process a large raw dataset without having to resort to feature engineering.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] However, deep learning algorithms still require careful preprocessing and cleaning of the input data.
[src:face-recognition-cv/feature-extraction] In addition, choosing the right architecture, hyperparameters, and optimization algorithm for a deep neural network can be a challenging and iterative process.
